From: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
Subject: [PATCH] ARM: dts: omap4-steelhead: pin the factory WiFi MAC in DT

The BCM4330 WiFi (brcmfmac, SDIO) has no on-device source for its per-device
factory MAC. Stock got it from the bootloader kernel command line
(androidboot.wifi_macaddr=, parsed by a board callback into the bcmdhd platform
data) which read it from the per-device efs/factory partition — a path we cannot
reproduce: our U-Boot does not pass it and CONFIG_CMDLINE_FORCE=y would discard
it anyway. The shipped nvram (brcmfmac4330-sdio.txt) carries only a generic
Broadcom placeholder macaddr=00:90:4c:c5:12:38, and brcmfmac ignores it because
the chip has a MAC burned in OTP (verified live 2026-07-16: overriding the nvram
macaddr and reloading the module left the permanent MAC at the OTP value
14:7d:c5:3a:35:b5, Murata OUI).

So wlan0 came up on the chip OTP MAC instead of the factory f8:8f:ca:20:48:e1,
which made its DHCP lease wander and show an empty hostname on the router (the
NetworkManager cloned-mac-address pin only patched the baked profile; a profile
created by nexusq-setupd during onboarding lost it and fell back to the OTP MAC).

This is the exact problem already solved for Bluetooth, whose factory MAC is
hardcoded in this DTS as `local-bd-address` for the same reason. Mirror it for
WiFi: brcmfmac's brcmf_of_probe() reads `local-mac-address` via
of_get_mac_address() into settings->mac and programs it over the OTP MAC, so the
per-device factory MAC becomes the interface's permanent address at the driver
level — no per-profile clone needed. The factory MACs are consecutive:
BT f8:8f:ca:20:49:e5, WiFi f8:8f:ca:20:48:e1.

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
---
 arch/arm/boot/dts/ti/omap/omap4-steelhead.dts | 4 ++++
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+)

--- a/arch/arm/boot/dts/ti/omap/omap4-steelhead.dts
+++ b/arch/arm/boot/dts/ti/omap/omap4-steelhead.dts
@@ -694,6 +694,10 @@
 		reg = <1>;
 		interrupt-parent = <&gpio2>;
 		interrupts = <21 IRQ_TYPE_LEVEL_HIGH>; /* gpio_53 */
 		interrupt-names = "host-wake";
+		/* Per-device factory WiFi MAC. brcmfmac has no on-device source for
+		 * it (nvram is a placeholder; OTP holds a generic Murata MAC), so pin
+		 * it here exactly as the BT node pins local-bd-address. (2026-07-16.) */
+		local-mac-address = [f8 8f ca 20 48 e1];
 	};
 };

